<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
<meta charset="UTF-8">
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
<title>Gradient Fade Example</title>

<style>
*{
    margin:0;
    padding:0;
    box-sizing:border-box;
}

body{
    font-family:Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;
    background:white;
}

/* Hero Section */
.hero{
    height:500px;
    background:url("https://picsum.photos/1600/900") center/cover no-repeat;
    display:flex;
    justify-content:center;
    align-items:center;
    color:white;
    font-size:48px;
    font-weight:bold;
}

/* White Fade */
.fade{
    height:150px;
    margin-top:-150px;
    background:linear-gradient(
        to bottom,
        rgba(255,255,255,0),
        rgba(255,255,255,1)
    );
}

/* Content */
.content{
    padding:60px;
    max-width:900px;
    margin:auto;
    line-height:1.8;
}

h2{
    margin-bottom:20px;
}

p{
    margin-bottom:20px;
}
</style>

</head>
<body>

<section class="hero">
    Hero Section
</section>

<div class="fade"></div>

<section class="content">
    <h2>Content Starts Here</h2>

    <p>
        This is the section below the hero. Notice how the image smoothly
        fades into the white background instead of ending abruptly.
    </p>

    <p>
        The gradient is created using a simple linear-gradient from
        transparent to white, while the negative margin pulls it over the
        bottom of the hero image.
    </p>

    <p>
        Scroll down to see how natural the transition looks.
    </p>
</section>

</body>
</html>
